com.ibm.team.repository.common.query

Enum IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.lang.Enum<IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern>
      • com.ibm.team.repository.common.query.IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern>
    Enclosing interface:
    IQueryGenerationOptions

    public static enum IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern
extends java.lang.Enum<IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePattern>
    Used to specify the pattern that should be used within the SQL generated for a query that ie executed in the context of a baseline.
    CLASSIC
    This is the default and should be best in most cases. That is, the vast majority of your queries should not need to call IQueryGenerationOptions.setBaselinePattern(BaselinePattern) at all. However, we have seen cases where this form performs poorly on DB2. If your query performance testing indicates that you have hit this problem then you should consider using one of the other two IQueryGenerationOptions.BaselinePatterns for the query in question.

    For the relevant part of the query, the query generator will produce SQL similar to that shown here in bold: 

     select t1q.*, t1v.item_type_dbid from queryable table t1q
 inner join repository.version t1v on t1v.state_id = t1q.state_id
 where t1v.item_type_dbid = ? and t1v.config_id = ? and t1v.created <= ?
 and not exists (select 1 from repository.version
                 where item_id = t1v.item_id and item_type_dbid = t1v.item_type_dbid and config_id = t1v.config_id
                 and created > t1v.created and created <= ?)
 and t1v.is_current in (0,1)
    MAX_GROUP_BY
    You should consider using this pattern only if your query performance testing has identified a baseline query for which CLASSIC performs unexpectedly slowly (and even then, only on the DB it performs poorly on).

    For the relevant part of the query, the query generator will produce SQL similar to that shown below in bold. Note that this uses a sub-select, the max(...)aggregate function , and a group by clause. One result of this approach is that we then need to pass the baseline's creation timestamp only once. 

     select t1q.*, t1v.item_type_dbid from queryable table t1q
 inner join (select t1w.item_id, max(t1w.created) created from repository.version t1w
             where t1w.item_type_dbid = ?
             and t1w.config_id = ?
             and t1w.created <= ?
             group by t1w.item_id) t1x on t1v.item_id = t1x.item_id and t1v.created = t1x.created
 where t1v.is_current in (0,1)
    TIMESTAMP_LITERALS
    You should consider using this pattern only if your query performance testing has identified a baseline query for which both CLASSIC and MAX_GROUP_BY perform unexpectedly slowly (and even then, only on the DB it performs poorly on). The SQL generated will be the same as for CLASSIC except that the two timestamps will be embedded as literals within the generated SQL (instead of being passed as query parameters). Generally, using query parameters is preferred and considered a best practice. However, we have found cases in DB2 where (evidently) passing the two timestamps as query parameters results in DB2 choosing a poor execution plan.

    For the relevant part of the query, the query generator will produce SQL similar to that shown here in bold: 

     select t1q.*, t1v.item_type_dbid from queryable table t1q
 inner join repository.version t1v on t1v.state_id = t1q.state_id
 where t1v.item_type_dbid = ? and t1v.config_id = ? and t1v.created <= 'timestamp literal'
 and not exists (select 1 from repository.version
                 where item_id = t1v.item_id and item_type_dbid = t1v.item_type_dbid and config_id = t1v.config_id
                 and created > t1v.created and created <= 'timestamp literal')
 and t1v.is_current in (0,1)
